nodes.documentation:
@title Arbitrable Deposit
 This is a a contract which allow for an owner deposit. Anyone besides the owner can seek arbitration/file a claim as a claimant.
To develop a contract inheriting from this one, you need to:
 - Redefine RULING_OPTIONS to explain the consequences of the possible rulings.
 - Redefine executeRuling while still calling super.executeRuling to implement the results of the arbitration.

claimResponse(uint256).details: Owner response to claimant. To be called when the owner initates a a response.

params._responseAmount: The counter-offer amount the Owner proposes to a claimant.

deposit().details: Owner deposit to contract. To be called when the owner makes a deposit.

makeClaim(uint256).details: File a claim against owner. To be called when someone makes a claim.

params._claimAmount: The proposed claim amount by the claimant.

payArbitrationFeeByClaimant().details: Pay the arbitration fee to raise a dispute. To be called by the claimant. UNTRUSTED. Note that this function mirror payArbitrationFeeByOwner.

payArbitrationFeeByOwner().details: Pay the arbitration fee to raise a dispute. To be called by the owner. UNTRUSTED. Note that the arbitrator can have createDispute throw, which will make this function throw and therefore lead to a party being timed-out. This is not a vulnerability as the arbitrator can rule in favor of one party anyway.

rule(uint256,uint256).details: Give a ruling for a dispute. Must be called by the arbitrator. The purpose of this function is to ensure that the address calling it has the right to rule on the contract.

params._disputeID: ID of the dispute in the Arbitrator contract.
params._ruling: Ruling given by the arbitrator. Note that 0 is reserved for "Not able/wanting to make a decision".

timeOutByClaimant().details: Pay claimant if owner fails to pay the fee.

timeOutByOwner().details: Reimburse owner if claimant fails to pay the fee.
